{
  "answer": "**'Maxims I' is chapter 6 of *Old English Elegies*, a collection of anonymous Old English poems sometimes classified among the elegies due to shared themes of transience, wisdom, and human experience.**[^1]\n\nThe gnomic line in question appears to refer to the maxim on royal generosity and marriage alliances, where a king secures a queen through exchange of valuables including rings (symbolizing treasure and reciprocity in Anglo-Saxon gift economy): \"A king must buy a queen with property, with cups and with rings; both must first be generous with gifts.\"[^2]\n\nThis reflects the cultural expectation that kings \"trade\" or distribute rings as rewards to retainers, fostering loyalty, though here it's framed in the context of bride-price.[^3]\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 6 (*Maxims I*), [chapter](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/06-maxims-i/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 6 (*Maxims I*), [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/06-maxims-i/translation/#p-84cf09).\n\n[^3]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 6 (*Maxims I*), [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/06-maxims-i/translation/#p-84cf09).",
